<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-vector-fields">
  <title>Vector fields</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret vector fields as functions assigning a vector to each point.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Examine key examples such as radial, rotational, and inverse-square fields in 2D and 3D.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          View vector fields as dynamical systems and study their streamlines.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        This is another way to visualize a multivariable function of multiple variables — vector input gives vector output.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        2D vector fields:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\bv{F}(x,y) \amp = (P(x,y),Q(x,y))</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = P(x,y)\,\uv{x}+Q(x,y)\,\uv{y}</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>
        Good examples are <m>(x,y)</m> and <m>(-y,x)</m>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        3D vector fields:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\bv{F}(x,y,z) \amp = (P(x,y,z),Q(x,y,z),R(x,y,z))</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = P(x,y,z)\,\uv{x}+Q(x,y,z)\,\uv{y}+R(x,y,z)\,\uv{z}</mrow>
      </md>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Inverse square fields
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Interpreting as a force field vs a velocity field
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        The Pólya vector field of a complex function <m>f(z)=u(x,y)+\ii v(x,y)</m> is given by:
        <me>
          \bv{F}(x,y) = u(x,y)\,\uv{x} - v(x,y)\,\uv{y}
        </me>.
        Note the minus sign in the second component. We'll see that minus sign throughout, and it'll become clear why it's useful.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
